    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Berenice Lowe (1896-1983) was a local historian and writer from Battle Creek, Michigan. Much of her research was devoted to the life and career of African American abolitionist Sojourner Truth.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The collection consists of two broad groupings of materials: collected articles, photographs, and other information relating to the life of Sojourner Truth; and papers relating to Lowe's various activities and interests, including Battle Creek history and personalities, travel diaries, and her friendship with writer Gerald Carson. In this last grouping of materials are collected letters of others, including autographs and papers of individuals, such as D. J. Van Schnell who wrote to members of the Oldfield family and included with his letters delightful watercolor drawings indicative of English life in the period especially of the late 1930s and the early years of the war.</p>
      <p>Most of the Sojourner Truth files have been microfilmed except for a folder of material which came to the library after the 1965 filming. A few photographs that were microfilmed in 1965 were reported missing. These images are only available on the microfilm.</p>
    </scopecontent>
